TY  - JOUR
AB  - This paper studies the welfare consequences of inflation and disinflation in a model in which firms incur a fixed cost of price adjustment. It is shown that a moderately increasing price level is associated with higher social welfare than a perfectly stable price level, and the model therefore provides theoretical support for the widespread belief that a little bit of inflation is good for the economy. Nevertheless, it is also true that the eradication of a moderate inflation leads to an increase in social welfare.
